          "body": "Esther's response to Mordecai's demand (4:11) is not evasion — it is accurate legal description. The law is explicit: any man or woman who approaches the king in the inner court unsummoned is put to death, unless the king extends the golden scepter. No exceptions. No appeal. And she has not been summoned in thirty days. Both facts are real, and both are relevant. Thirty days of royal silence means she has no current momentum of favor; she cannot assume the scepter will be extended. She is being asked to walk into the most restricted space in the empire, uninvited, without assurance, on behalf of a people whose identity she has concealed. Her description of the law is not an excuse; it is an honest statement of what it will cost. The pastoral significance is pointed: honest acknowledgment of the cost is not the same as refusal. Esther is not yet saying no. She is saying, 'Do you understand what you are asking?' Mordecai's answer in verses 13-14 is: yes, and it doesn't change the call."
