        "range": "4:10-12",
        "excerpt": "All the king's servants and the people of the king's provinces know that for any man or woman who comes to the king to the inner court who is not summoned, he has but one law, that he be put to death.",
        "body": "Esther's response through Hathach (4:11) is often read as reluctance or cowardice. A more careful reading reveals something different: honest, detailed acknowledgment of the specific cost. She does not say no. She says, here is what you are asking me to walk into. She names the law precisely: inner court, unsummoned, one law, death — unless the scepter. She adds the personal detail: thirty days without a summons. She is providing Mordecai with the full intelligence picture before committing to the mission.\n\nThe detail of the thirty days is not self-pity; it is strategic information. In the Persian court, royal favor was dynamic, not static. A queen who had not been summoned in a month had no current reading of the king's disposition toward her. The scepter could be withheld. The fact that Esther was Ahasuerus's queen offered no automatic guarantee — the book's opening chapters have already established that queens can be deposed without explanation (Vashti, 1:19). Esther's caution is calibrated, not craven.\n\nEsther may also be wondering whether this is the moment. The decree is irrevocable (cf. 1:19; 8:8) — can an unsanctioned approach to the king actually reverse it? She has no legal mechanism, no precedent, no plan. She has only the possibility of the scepter. Her statement of the law is not a refusal but a request for clarification: do you understand what this costs, and do you still believe it must be done? Mordecai's answer in verses 13-14 makes clear: yes, and more than you realize.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Dat* (law, v.11) appears four times in the chapter — the word frames both the crisis (edict of annihilation) and the barrier (law against approach). *Sharvit ha-zahav* (the golden scepter, v.11) — *sharvit* appears only in Esther in the Hebrew Bible; it is the visible symbol of the king's sovereign discretion, the one variable that can override the law of death."
